    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian" other_reader="Unknown">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="full_page" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        On the cover of this book you have a curious Impression in vellom of [the] Pictures of Melanthon &amp; Luther - 
                        Under one are these words
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="full_page" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Forma, Philippe, tua est, sed Mens tua nescia pingi nota est ante Bonis, et tua est. 1565 <!--JG: These words appear in other books as well, as part of a larger text. See, for example, the back panel of the book 'De Statu Religionis et Republicae Carolo V Caesare Commentarii'. See: https://hrs48.wordpress.com/tag/reformation/ and http://www.inschriften.net/goettingen/inschrift/nr/di019-0132.html#content.-->
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                This is your image, Philip, but your famous mind is unknown to good men, and yours is. 1565 <!--JG: Unsure, I'll ask Lisa/Tony-->
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="full_page" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        On the other side under Luther are these words - 
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="full_page" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Nosse cujus faciem Lutheri hanc cerne Tabellam, si Mentem Libros consule, certus eris.
                        <!-- JE: this is garbled as well - 'cujus' should be 'cupis' -->
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                If you want to know the face of Luther, look at this picture. If you want to know his mind, look in his books and you will be sure.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
    </annotation>
